<font color="#FF0000">&quot;WIFE LEFT BEHIND&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1  7:00:53 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Because the war divided our society so much, when you were<br>
a &quot;wife left behind&quot; you were also a &quot;wife left alone&quot; in<br>
most cases.  One day when I was feeling especially lonely,<br>
I called someone whom I thought was a friend and she told<br>
me I should check out one of those self-help groups of <br>
wives left behind.  Perhaps she thought she was doing me<br>
a favor, but it hurt.  I didn't want to discuss my feelings<br>
with strangers - I wanted to talk to my friends.  Yet none<br>
of my friends or family members had spouses/boyfriends in<br>
Vietnam.  I was amazed at how isolated I felt.  I stopped <br>
telling people my husband was in Vietnam - most of the time<br>
I felt like a pariah.  This even from older people who pro-<br>
fessed to be understanding of war.  To this day if I refer<br>
to my husband as a Vietnam War Vet, some people look at me as if they are looking for scars where he has beat me.  He is a good man who would never hurt anyone.  He never even shot a gun in a combat situation - his job was to make sure the troops got fed.  This didn't stop him from nearly getting killed several times.  That's the worse thing about<br>
being the wife left behind - the isolation.<br><br>

